    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_529992">ArsTechnica <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2012/08/own-e-books-publishers-to-pay-back-millions-over-price-fixing-charges/" target="_blank">is reporting</a> that three publishers accused of price fixing charges (Hachette Book Group, HarperCollins, and Simon &amp; Schuster) have reached a settlement worth $69 million, plus they agree to terminate their 'agency model' which allowed the publishers to set the retail price.  The two remaining publishers (Macmillan and Penguin) as well as distributor Apple are still set for a trial sometime next year.<br />
<br />
I've completely ignored ebooks because I like paperbacks and because of the blatant collusion setting ebook prices higher than paperback prices, but now that I have a tablet (Asus Transformer TF300T for home as well as a cheap 7&quot; tablet I bring to work) I'll probably look into ebooks from the publishers who have settled.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
