</div>I'm not really following your train of thought here? I don't think expecting an electronic version of a book you buy in print is like your example it all. It's more like buying a DVD which comes with a digital copy for your computer.<br />
<br />
When I buy a book in print I expect a certain percentage of that price to go towards the materials: paper, ink, binding, etc. If I were to buy an ebook, I expect to pay the same price as the printed book <i>minus </i>the cost of materials. I've never bought an ebook (I don't have a reader outside the Kindle app on my phone), but I was shocked and disappointed to see the prices publishers were trying to charge for their ebooks compared to the printed versions.</div>
