</div>I agree with Kambic here.  It's not that I expect them to replace my DVD with a Bluray, it's that I expect a digital copy to come with my Bluray - which most companies are doing nowadays.<br />
<br />
I'm not expecting them to give me free digital copies of books I already own - though that would be nice, it'd be absurd to expect.  However, new books should come with a digital copy, as there is NO manufacturing cost involved.  As most books are digitally written nowadays in some fashion anyway (Stephen King - or was it Dean Koontz? - handwriting on notebook paper aside), an ebook version costs next to nothing to create and distribute.  The bandwidth MIGHT cost them a nickel.  Make the book 8.99 instead of 7.99, I have no problem with that.  Asking me to pay 7.99 for a physical copy, then 7.99 for a digital copy...  there's a problem.</div>
