		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">When I buy a book in print I expect a certain percentage of that price to go towards the materials: paper, ink, binding, etc. If I were to buy an ebook, I expect to pay the same price as the printed book <i>minus </i>the cost of materials. I've never bought an ebook (I don't have a reader outside the Kindle app on my phone), but I was shocked and disappointed to see the prices publishers were trying to charge for their ebooks compared to the printed versions.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>However in place of the materials you do have the cost of having someone format the book for eReaders and make sure everything displays correctly. But you are right, even with that the cost of that should be substantially less than having to use a printing press and all that stuff. And yes, some of those ebook prices, haha, yessss, paying more for a digital copy that's often DRM'd, can't be resold or have severe restrictions on loaning them to your friends... AND cannot be whipped out to be signed by your favorite author... that's more the kind of lack of understanding of the digital age you'd expect from the comic book industry than books. I mean I love some authors, even if they write books thick enough that you could kill a man by hitting him with one, and I do love being able to read those books without straining my wrists with their paperbricks... but not enough to pay the exact same for an ebook as a hardcover.<br />
<br />
<br />
Edit: Oh and I would love getting a digital copy. I especially don't think that's too much to ask for when I'm buying their new hardcovers at ... well they ain't cheap. A scratch card with a code that gave me a digital copy on the format/service of my choice doesn't seem unreasonable if I'm spending 35 bucks on new dead tree book.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
