    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_530021">There's a lot more to the production of an electronic book than just the lack of using paper and ink.  It's not like the Fairy Godmother appears, waves her magic wand, and turns a pumpkin into the latest Grisham novel on your tablet.  Electronics books are still formatted, tested, distributed, and supported, not to mention all the legal considerations that take place between author and publisher.  Work is still done, so it wouldn't make sense for a publishing house to put in the time and expenditure of producing an eBook just to give it away while at the same time trying to sell the printed version.  Also, in many cases the people who produce and sell you printed books are not the same people that produce and sell you eBooks.<br />
<br />
In addition, there's the nightmarish subject of geographic restrictions.  Books that are available in printed form in a given country will not necessarily be available in another form in that same country.  This is because the law is different regarding printed books and electronic books.  There's a really good examination on this here: <a href="http://bitethebook.com/2010/09/20/territory-wars/" target="_blank">http://bitethebook.com/2010/09/20/territory-wars/</a><br />
<br />
Ultimately, this court ruling is a good thing, for consumers anyway.  Bookstores can begin applying discounts to books made by those three publishers again, but Amazon will get to continue their practice of losing money on eBooks to drive all competitors out of business.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
