<a href="showpost.php?p=530047&amp;postcount=19" target="new" rel="nofollow" id="postcount530047" name="19" class="pcount"><strong>#19</strong></a>

			
		</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_530047">It's good to have someone from within the industry who can kinda play devil's advocate here, but I hope that what we are saying still makes sense to you, Deltar.<br />
<br />
I'm not saying that ebooks should be free or only cost pennies just because you can make copies literally as fast as computer processing power allows people to download them. However, I expect that whatever the breakdown is for the cost of a physical book is going to be extremely similar to the breakdown of cost for an electronic book (royalties to the author, formatting, legal stuff, profit, etc.) - <i>minus</i> the cost of physical materials (paper, ink, binding, jacket).<br />
<br />
I'm going to have to be provided with some pretty solid data to justify pricing an electronic book at <i>more </i>than the cost of a paperback.<br />
<br />
Not providing a digital copy with a physical copy? Eh, that's not something I think should be demanded, though it would certainly score huge bonus points with the consumer. It's definitely something I'd support, but I can see it going either way. Pricing a digital book equal to or even higher than it's physical counterpart? No, sorry, I just don't swallow that at all.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
