    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_530058"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Deltar Battlewall said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">So because technology is so convenient that it allows you to read a book on your phone, you don't think authors should be paid the same for the art they produce?<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Who ever said you have to buy a book twice?  If you like printed books, buy those.  If you like electronic books, buy those instead.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Do I think the Author should be paid the same? Yes, do I think the publisher should be? Absolutely not.<br />
<br />
Books much like DVD's and music have quite a bit of production, packaging and shipping costs that simply don't exist in ebooks. Now if we were still talking about older books where they were typed up on a typewriter and needed conversion sure you have an argument. However there isn't a single book being produced that isn't typed up on a computer and thus already in digital format. Is some effort required to format it for ereaders? yes, is it anywhere near the effort to print? not even close. Now if we are talking about those purchasing the ebook without the hard copy, then sure they need to pay a higher price but hardly the same as a hard copy as the ebook just doesn't have the production costs and never will.<br />
<br />
I like most here don't buy ebooks exclusively, I want them as an added convenience to my regular book purchase for those times when hauling a book  isn't viable. I don't mind the author being paid, but I am absolutely against the publisher charging like it costs them the same to produce copies of ebooks which it flatly doesn't.</div>
