    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_538777"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Kambic said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">I expect that whatever the breakdown is for the cost of a physical book is going to be extremely similar to the breakdown of cost for an electronic book (royalties to the author, formatting, legal stuff, profit, etc.) - <i>minus</i> the cost of physical materials (paper, ink, binding, jacket).</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>I agree. An ebook is a different format, to the point where it practically needs reformatting from scratch with a different layout for each of the two formats.<br />
<br />
To use a music analogy, it's like vinyl and MP3; both formats come from one source, but they both need to be created from the original masters and cannot just be copied from one format to the other.<br />
<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">I'm going to have to be provided with some pretty solid data to justify pricing an electronic book at <i>more </i>than the cost of a paperback.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Cynical answer one: Supply and demand? If people pay that amount (and they will, especially Apple customers), then that is the value of the item.<br />
<br />
Cynical answer two: The brick and mortar shops, the big ones, would boycott any publisher selling ebooks for much less than the physical copy. While the majority of sales happen to be physical books, no publisher can afford to lose physical sales. This is the same reason why digital games and boxed games cost roughly the same, even if half of us wait for Steam 'sales' before buying the games; they still can't afford to lose boxed sales. <br />
<br />
The truth: It is six of one and half a dozen of the other. Their hands might be tied by physical shops when it comes to pricing, but they don't really <i>mind</i> making higher profits on ebooks.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
